  walkthrough: `The CNS quarter crowns the highest hill in Pharma City — a labyrinth of cobbled lanes lit by oil-lamps that flicker and swell with every synaptic wave. From the central crossroads you can peer down on all the other districts below; up here the air is thinner, the silences more complete, and the consequences of getting the chemistry wrong more sudden. Six wards radiate outward like spokes: the Sleep Quarter (its windows permanently frosted, warm amber light pooling under low doorframes), the Mood Gardens (a walled park where the flowers bloom or wilt depending on monoamine rainfall), the Asylum Walls (tall grey stone, iron gates, faint rhythmic chanting), the Seizure Chapel (a vaulted nave trembling with suppressed electrical charge), the Tremor Walk (cobbles worn smooth by patients who shuffle here daily), and the Anaesthetic Theatre (a circular glass rotunda behind which figures slip in and out of stillness). Streets end abruptly in fog at the district's edges so each ward feels sealed from the next — a deliberate architecture of compartmentalised consciousness.

Deeper into the hill, where the oil-lamps give way to guttering red torches, lies the Opium Den: a subterranean courtyard paved with smooth river-stones, its archways draped with damp silk, the air thick with the sweet weight of the mu receptor. Above ground the Pharmacy-Hill Clock Tower keeps time for the entire quarter — its pendulum swings in exact 90-minute cycles to mark the REM rhythm, and when it strikes midnight the oil-lamps dim throughout the Sleep Quarter simultaneously. Every building on the hill is named for the drug it houses; every drug carries the exact latitude of its action inscribed above its doorway; every wall bears a contraindication plaque in raised iron lettering, because on the CNS hill a dosing error can silence the clock altogether.`,
